<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <%- include('partials/head') %>
</head>
<body>

<%- include('partials/header') %>

<main>

  <!-- ── Hero ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="hero" style="padding: 3.5rem 0;">
    <div class="hero__image-slot" aria-hidden="true"></div>
    <div class="container">
      <div class="hero__content">
        <span class="hero__eyebrow">Visiting &amp; Exploring</span>
        <h1>Activities on the Island</h1>
        <p class="hero__description">
          Hiking the lighthouse trail, kayaking the harbour, foraging wild berries,
          birding the headlands. McNutt's Island rewards those who make the crossing.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── Getting Here ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="editorial">
        <div>
          <span class="section__eyebrow">First Things First</span>
          <h2>Getting to the Island</h2>
          <p>
            McNutt's Island is accessible only by water. There is no public ferry service —
            visitors arrive by private boat, kayak, or chartered water taxi from the
            Gunning Cove boat launch, approximately 15 minutes from Shelburne town centre.
          </p>
          <p>
            The crossing from Gunning Cove is roughly 800 metres across sheltered water.
            Conditions in Shelburne Harbour are generally calm, but weather can change quickly,
            particularly in spring and fall. Check the forecast and tide tables before crossing.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong>Gunning Cove</strong> has a public boat launch and limited parking.
            From Shelburne, take Highway 3 west, turn onto Gunning Cove Road, and follow
            to the water.
          </p>
          <blockquote>
            There are no services on McNutt's Island — no convenience store, no cell service,
            no medical facilities. Come prepared with everything you need.
          </blockquote>
        </div>
        <div style="display:flex; flex-direction:column; gap:1rem;">
          <div class="editorial__image img-placeholder" style="min-height: 200px;">
            <span class="img-placeholder__icon" aria-hidden="true">&#9973;</span>
            <span class="img-placeholder__label">Boat launch photograph</span>
          </div>
          <div class="card card--sand">
            <div class="card__body">
              <h4 style="margin-bottom:.5rem;">Quick Facts</h4>
              <ul style="font-size:.875rem; line-height:2;">
                <li>Launch: Gunning Cove, Shelburne</li>
                <li>Crossing: ~800m, 15 min by kayak</li>
                <li>Services: None — self-sufficient</li>
                <li>Cell service: None</li>
                <li>Season: Year-round access</li>
                <li>Camping: Permitted with care</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── Activities grid ───────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="section section--alt">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section__header text-center">
        <span class="section__eyebrow">What to Do</span>
        <h2>Activities</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="grid grid--2">

        <div class="editorial">
          <div class="editorial__image img-placeholder" style="min-height: 220px; max-width: 280px;">
            <span class="img-placeholder__label">Trail photograph</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <h3>Hiking</h3>
            <p>
              The lighthouse trail winds through Acadian forest and along the island's western
              shore to the 1788 lighthouse at McNutt's Head. The round trip is approximately
              6 kilometres of moderate walking, with excellent views of the Atlantic and
              the harbour approaches.
            </p>
            <p>
              The trail is informal — bring good footwear and be prepared for wet ground
              in the bog sections. The lighthouse grounds are open to visitors.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="editorial">
          <div class="editorial__image img-placeholder" style="min-height: 220px; max-width: 280px;">
            <span class="img-placeholder__label">Kayak photograph</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <h3>Kayaking</h3>
            <p>
              Sea kayaking around McNutt's Island is one of the finest paddles on the South Shore.
              The sheltered harbour side is suitable for beginners; the outer coast requires
              more experience and attention to weather.
            </p>
            <p>
              Kayak rentals are available in Shelburne. Paddlers should be comfortable
              self-rescuing in cold water and aware of tidal currents at the island's points.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="editorial">
          <div class="editorial__image img-placeholder" style="min-height: 220px; max-width: 280px;">
            <span class="img-placeholder__label">Berries photograph</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <h3>Foraging</h3>
            <p>
              The island's open areas produce an abundance of wild blueberries, raspberries,
              and wild strawberries in summer. Chanterelle mushrooms are found throughout
              the forest after rain. Beach pea and sea rocket are edible coastal plants.
            </p>
            <p>
              Forage lightly and knowledgeably. Take only what you'll use; leave the rest
              for the animals and for next season. Never harvest from unfamiliar plants.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="editorial">
          <div class="editorial__image img-placeholder" style="min-height: 220px; max-width: 280px;">
            <span class="img-placeholder__label">Binoculars/birding photograph</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <h3>Birding</h3>
            <p>
              McNutt's Island is exceptional birding territory — bald eagles year-round,
              migratory songbirds in spring and fall, nesting osprey and great blue herons
              through summer, and wintering sea ducks offshore.
            </p>
            <p>
              Bring binoculars and a field guide. Spring migration (late April–May) and
              fall migration (August–October) are the most productive times for warbler
              and shorebird diversity.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── Accommodations & Visitor Info ─────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section__header">
        <span class="section__eyebrow">Plan Your Visit</span>
        <h2>Visitor Information</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="grid grid--2">
        <div>
          <h3>Staying on the Island</h3>
          <p>
            There are no commercial accommodations on McNutt's Island. Camping is possible
            with appropriate preparation — you are responsible for carrying in everything
            you need and carrying out all waste. There are no facilities.
          </p>
          <p>
            Several island residents and property owners provide seasonal accommodation;
            contact the McNutt's Island Alliance for referrals to properties that may be
            available for short-term rental.
          </p>
          <h3 class="mt-3">Staying in Shelburne</h3>
          <p>
            The town of Shelburne, 15 minutes from Gunning Cove, offers a full range of
            accommodations from B&amp;Bs to motels. Shelburne is a heritage town with
            excellent restaurants, the Shelburne County Museum, and the historic waterfront.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3>What to Bring</h3>
          <ul style="line-height: 2.2; font-size: .95rem;">
            <li>Water — at least 2L per person</li>
            <li>Food for the day (nothing available on island)</li>
            <li>Rain gear — weather changes quickly</li>
            <li>Warm layers, even in summer</li>
            <li>Bug repellent (summer blackflies and mosquitoes)</li>
            <li>Sunscreen and hat</li>
            <li>First aid kit</li>
            <li>A charged GPS device or downloaded offline map</li>
            <li>VHF marine radio if boating</li>
            <li>A bag for your waste</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="mt-2 text-muted" style="font-size:.875rem;">
            There is no cell service on the island. Let someone onshore know your plan
            and expected return time before you cross.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ── Responsible visiting ──────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="section section--dark">
    <div class="container container--narrow text-center">
      <h2>Visit Responsibly</h2>
      <p style="color:var(--sand); max-width:520px; margin: 1rem auto 0;">
        McNutt's Island is a working landscape — fishing families depend on it,
        wildlife nests on it, and a fragile ecosystem depends on visitors who
        tread lightly. Leave no trace. Respect nesting areas. Stay on established
        paths where possible. Take only photographs.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

</main>

<%- include('partials/footer') %>
<script src="/js/main.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
